{"id": "38131", "title": "Bug 38131: ajc needs -d option while correctly compiling classes from a subpackage", "description": "I am using ajc 1.1rc1. This is a regression since rc1 and a deviation from javac. I am guessing this may have something to do with a change in the underlying Eclipse compiler.

To reproduce the bug:
1. Create a class in a subpackage like this:
   package subpackage;

   public class Test {
       public static void main(String[] args) {
           System.out.println("Hello");
       }
   }

2. Compile the class using the following command:
   ajc subpackage\Test.java

Expected behavior: The test.class file should be put in the subpackage\subpackage directory.

Actual behavior: A new subpackage directory is created within the existing subpackage directory, resulting in the java command throwing the exception:
   Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: subpackage/Test

A workaround for this problem is to run either of the following commands after ajc compiles the class:
   ajc -d . subpackage\Test.java
   javac subpackage\Test.java

This will fix the problem.", "OB": "The test.class file is then put in the subpackage\subpackage directory. Running the java command results in an exception:
   Exception in thread "main" java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: subpackage/Test

This issue can be resolved by running either of the following commands after compiling with ajc:
   ajc -d .
   javac subpackage\Test.java

This will create the necessary subpackage directory under the existing subpackage directory and fix the problem.", "EB": "", "SR": ""}

